<paragraph blockId="75.[106,745,428,519]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">T y p e s t r a t u m a n d a g e. Lower member of the Almargem Formation; Early Cretaceous (late Barremianearly Aptian).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[144,493,543,567]" box="[144,493,543,567]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">D i a g n o s i s. As for the genus.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[106,745,591,682]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">
D i m e n s i o n s. Length of fruit: 
<quantity box="[504,588,591,615]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
; width of fruit: 
<quantity box="[106,191,624,648]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
. Long axis of pollen grains parallel with the colpus: about 18 µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[106,745,705,994]" lastBlockId="75.[820,1460,151,561]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[555,744,705,729]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Vedresia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elliptica">
<emphasis box="[555,744,705,729]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Vedresia elliptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on a single fruit that has been studied only by SEM and details of its internal structure are unknown. The fruit is small, elliptical in lateral view, and there is no attachment scar or scars from detached floral organs (
<figureCitation box="[586,733,838,862]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="77.[125,206,1953,1974]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-11@77.[559,1013,922,1536]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Text-fig. 49. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images of Vedresia elliptica gen. et sp. nov. (a–c) and a multicarpellate fruit of Choffaticarpus compactus gen. et sp. nov. and associated pollen (d–j); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; small fruit showing apical stigmatic region with attached pollen; b) Group of pollen grains from the stigmatic surface of the fruit in (a) showing the long colpus and reticulate tectum; c) Pollen grains from the stigmatic surface showing the long colpus and well developed reticulum, with smooth muri and short columellae" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386367/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Text-fig. 49a</figureCitation>
). The outline of the fossil strongly suggests that the fruit is unilocular and contains a single seed. Slight irregularities in the fruit surface also suggest that the enclosed seed had an irregular, reticulate surface. There are no clear indications of oil cells in the fruit wall. The stigmatic area is sessile, indistinct and has numerous pollen grains, all of the same kind, adhering to the stigma (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1266,216,240]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="77.[125,206,1953,1974]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-11@77.[559,1013,922,1536]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Text-fig. 49. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images of Vedresia elliptica gen. et sp. nov. (a–c) and a multicarpellate fruit of Choffaticarpus compactus gen. et sp. nov. and associated pollen (d–j); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; small fruit showing apical stigmatic region with attached pollen; b) Group of pollen grains from the stigmatic surface of the fruit in (a) showing the long colpus and reticulate tectum; c) Pollen grains from the stigmatic surface showing the long colpus and well developed reticulum, with smooth muri and short columellae" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386367/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Text-fig. 49b</figureCitation>
). Pollen is broadly elliptical to circular in equatorial outline, and monocolpate with a long colpus that extends for the full length of the grains. Grains are semitectate-reticulate and heterobrochate. Lumina over most of the pollen surface are of various sizes, up to about 1.5 µm in diameter. Bordering the colpus margin lumina are smaller and grade into foveae (
<figureCitation box="[1301,1447,409,433]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="77.[125,206,1953,1974]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-11@77.[559,1013,922,1536]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Text-fig. 49. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) and synchrotron radiation X-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM) images of Vedresia elliptica gen. et sp. nov. (a–c) and a multicarpellate fruit of Choffaticarpus compactus gen. et sp. nov. and associated pollen (d–j); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; small fruit showing apical stigmatic region with attached pollen; b) Group of pollen grains from the stigmatic surface of the fruit in (a) showing the long colpus and reticulate tectum; c) Pollen grains from the stigmatic surface showing the long colpus and well developed reticulum, with smooth muri and short columellae" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386367/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Text-fig. 49c</figureCitation>
). Muri are smooth, lack supratectal ornamentation and are supported by long, scattered columellae. The reticulum is only loosely attached to the foot layer and has been lost in several of the grains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[820,1460,584,995]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. The similarities of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[1019,1205,617,641]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Vedresia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elliptica">
<emphasis box="[1019,1205,617,641]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Vedresia elliptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fruit and its associated pollen grains to fruits of 
<taxonomicName box="[1118,1277,649,673]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Canrightiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1118,1277,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Canrightiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2011" box="[1342,1459,649,673]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Canrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1342,1459,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Canrightia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and their associated pollen grains strongly suggest a relationship to the clade comprising extant 
<taxonomicName box="[1356,1452,713,736]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Ascarina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1356,1452,713,736]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Ascarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[820,953,745,769]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Chloranthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[820,953,745,769]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Chloranthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1007,1119,745,769]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Sarcandra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1007,1119,745,769]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Sarcandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, among extant 
<taxonomicName box="[1286,1455,745,769]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Chloranthaceae</taxonomicName>
. However, information on internal structures including seed coat anatomy is lacking and assignment of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[1297,1388,810,834]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Vedresia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1297,1388,810,834]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Vedresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. BR. ex SIMS" authorityYear="1821" box="[820,968,842,866]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Chloranthales</taxonomicName>
is currently not secure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[820,1460,584,995]" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">
Pollen grains associated with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[1178,1364,874,898]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Vedresia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elliptica">
<emphasis box="[1178,1364,874,898]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Vedresia elliptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2019" box="[1020,1291,906,930]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Eckhartia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="75" pageNumber="228" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brevicolumella">
<emphasis box="[1020,1291,906,930]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Eckhartia brevicolumella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see p. 210 and 
<figureCitation box="[820,948,938,962]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="58.[147,228,1843,1864]" captionTargetBox="[154,1457,151,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-1@58.[154,1457,151,1823]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="Text-fig. 37. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of anthers and monocolpate pollen of Eckhartia brevicolumella gen. et sp. nov. from stamen fragment; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Dithecate, tetrasporangiate anther partially split along the elongated sporangia; b) Dithecate, tetrasporangiate anther; c) Holotype; distal view of pollen grain from holotype showing the long colpus with a distinct margin and a heterobrochate reticulum; d) Distal view of pollen grain from a stamen fragment showing long colpus, colpus margin and heterobrochate reticulum; e) Inner surface of anther wall from stamen fragmentshowing densely spaced dentate orbicules; f) Lateral view of pollen grains from stamen showing the psilate to foveolate-microreticulate colpus margin; g) Detail of pollen grain from holotype showing the slightly rounded profile of the muri, the short, densely spaced columellae and the dentate orbicules. Specimens, TV44-S136662 (a), TV44-S149204 (b), TV44-S136760 (holotype; c, g), TV44-S148021 (d, e), TV44-S136752 (f). Scale bars 300 Μm (a, b), 6 Μm (c, d, f), 3 Μm (e, g)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386327/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="228">Text-fig. 37</figureCitation>
) and it is possible that they were produced by the same species, or a very similar kind of plant.
</paragraph>
